docs.abstract: President Trump tweeted on Wednesday that Mr. Clapper, the former director of national intelligence, said he “should be happy that the F.B.I. was spying on his campaign.” Mr. Clapper did not say that.
docs.snippet: President Trump tweeted on Wednesday that Mr. Clapper, the former director of national intelligence, said he “should be happy that the F.B.I. was spying on his campaign.” Mr. Clapper did not say that.
docs.lead_paragraph: Mr. Trump is referring to comments by James R. Clapper Jr., who was the director of national intelligence under former President Barack Obama, that were made on “The View” on Tuesday. But Mr. Clapper never said what Mr. Trump claimed he did. In fact, he said the opposite.

headline.main: Trump Incorrectly Quotes James Clapper to Falsely Claim F.B.I. Spied on Campaign

docs.abstract: The president claimed that the European Union had a $151 billion trade surplus with the United States. It’s $101 billion.
docs.snippet: The president claimed that the European Union had a $151 billion trade surplus with the United States. It’s $101 billion.
docs.lead_paragraph: Mr. Trump’s numbers are off. The European Union had a $153 billion trade surplus in goods with the United States in 2017 and a total trade surplus of $101 billion when trade in services is included.

headline.main: Trump Exaggerates Trade Deficit With European Union by $50 Billion
